50490 Damansara City, Damansara Heights, Kuala Lumpur

location.address: 3F, Isetan The Japan Store, Lot 10 Shopping Centre.

formattedAddress: block A1-LEVEL G2 , Unit 01 SOLARIS DUTAMAS, (No.1 Jalan Dutamas 1 ,)
location.address: block A1-LEVEL G2 , Unit 01 SOLARIS DUTAMAS,

tip.text: Taste-wise, it's not as authentic as I would hope. But the dishes are certainly value for money. Would definitely return. If this is your first time and you want something safe, try the Pad Thai! ;)
These "gong pian" or Chinese bagels as I call 'em are so good! Crispy on the outside with the savoury wilted onions on the inside. One is probably not enough! A must have when you're in town.

venue.name: 曾家福州光饼 Cheong Cia Gong Pian

tip.text: RM14 per portion which is large enough for two persons. I like mine only with lean meat. Yum!

venue.name: Ah Sang Bah Kut Teh (亚汕肉骨茶)

tip.text: If this is your first time, order the signature deep fried brinjal and the minced meat tofu. They are both stellar. Would surely return. Parking inside the building is rather pricey at RM3 per entry.

location.crossStreet: Jalan SS9/2, Seri Setia, Sungai Way
formattedAddress: Lot 1-12, 1st Floor, Plaza Seri Setia (Jalan SS9/2, Seri Setia, Sungai Way)

venue.name: Restaurant Hua Xing 华绅风味食馆

tip.text: The place for the poshest kind of breakfast. The haggis with fried duck eggs is my favourite! Or if you want something sweet, go for the pancakes.
Love this indie-luxury hotel. The location is perfect, close to the Natural History Museum and the posh neighbourhood of Kensington. If you can, try the afternoon tea at Townhouse Restaurant!

venue.name: Funny Mountain Tau Fu Fah (奇峰豆腐花)
Restoran Lou Wong Tauge Ayam KueTiau (老黄芽菜鸡沙河粉)
曾家福州光饼 Cheong Cia Gong Pian

tip.text: Repurposed shipping containers made cool. Tons of eateries and shops to try out. Perfect summer hangout spot.
Truffles are amazing. You can try them before buying, ask the friendly staff members. I love the iced hot chocolate, a bit of an oxymoron but yummy!
Grungy side of London. And I love it!
Come here on a Sunday to experience the market at its peak, as everything is open then. Come with an empty stomach and a fully charged camera. Lots to eat and plenty to snap.
The salt beef bagel is soooo good! Price: £3.10 (as of September 2016)
Go to the rooftop for amazing views of St Paul's Cathedral. It's free!
Love the installations here. They do change them each year which is rather nice. Definitely a must visit if you're in Hyde Park.

Must try list: sausage frm Boston Sausage, chorizo roll frm Brindisa, grilled cheese sandwich/raclette frm Kappacasein, scotch eggs frm ScotchTails, anything frm Bread Ahead, oysters frm ShellSeekers.
Hipster paradise in the heart of Brixton. If you don't know what to go for, try Mama's Jerk and order the wings! You won't regret it.
Afternoon tea was such a delight. Service was prompt and perfect and the scones were heavenly. At £30 per person it might be a bit on the pricey side but well worth the experience.

The seats are really uncomfortable. And the ventilation is non-existent. They should at least upgrade them. But I sat through it all for Cursed Child. The awesomeness of the play made up for all that.
I bought my tickets one year in advance even before my flight tickets and hotel reservations. It was worth the wait. Definitely an experience I will forever hold dear. #keepthesecrets

venue.name: Harry Potter and the Cursed Child - Parts One and Two

tip.text: If you could, stay at Shangri-La at The Shard for even a night. It's worth every pound spent.
Such a pretty pub. One of the most beautiful in London, if I can say so myself.
The views here are amazing. Ask for a room that faces the Gherkin and Walkie Talkie building. You can use the binoculars to peek at how Londoners work. Don't forget to visit the Sky Pool!

contact.facebookName: Shangri-La Hotel, At The Shard, London

tip.text: Take a seat by the window and enjoy the planes taking off from the tarmac. Ask for a smoothie if you so wish.
Much better than the lounge in KLIA. Food is just okay...
It's walking distance to The Langham...
The breakfast here is amazing. Order the full English breakfast!
Rooms are well-appointed. Classic luxury is how I would describe them. Location is perfect as it is just a few minutes away from the tube. Lady Gaga stays here whenever she is in London... ;)
A nice lounge to wait before your flight. Food is lacklustre, wouldn't hurt if there's more variety.

formattedAddress: LNG1, Mezzanine Level, Satellite Terminal (KUL Airport)

contact.facebookName: Shangri-La Hotel, At The Shard, London
Shangri-La Hotel, At The Shard, London

location.crossStreet: Royal Festival Hall, The Queen's Walk
formattedAddress: Under the Bridge  Riverside Level, (Royal Festival Hall, The Queen's Walk)

venue.name: Warner Bros. Studio Tour London - The Making of Harry Potter

tip.text: Not to my liking (others might like it), as the noodles are too clumpy. Nothing spectacular about the taste either. The filling is generous for the wan tan though - a mix of pork and prawn.
Every table would have a plate of char siew. So you know you can't go wrong with that. It's really that good! The eggplant with long beans though, is just okay.

venue.name: The Home Cooking Dishes (鼎豐 (家鄉菜) 饭店)

tip.text: The Royal Palace Suite is huge! A bit dated though (needs an upgrade) and they don't have enough plug points in the room. Utilise the club facilities fully when you're here!
The ddukbogi (Korean rice cakes) is a must order. Trust me. The meats are all good too. Can't go wrong with Korean BBQ.
The sate here is so good! I can't stop eating them. If you don't know how many to order, about 20 sticks per person should be enough. I skipped the rice cakes.
You need to order your Pie Susu in advance (at least a day before). I did the mistake of walking in, hoping there would be some but nope, all gone. And I went rather early in the morning!

location.address: Jalan Dewi Sri VIII Blok B-8
formattedAddress: Jalan Dewi Sri VIII Blok B-8

tip.text: So delicious! A must have when you're here. Can't go wrong with them.
Here for the amazing cliff-side views while hanging out with the surfers. Truly worth the journey. Tip: Don't come here by taxi as they ban them here. Rent a private driver instead.
I'm all about the suite life here. Stayed at the Grand Suite King and it's amazing how luxe and huge the room is. Couldn't ask for anything better. Tip: Ask for the newly renovated rooms!

Best time to visit: late afternoons or evenings when the weather is cooler and lighting for photos is perfect, especially with the changing colours of the skyline. A must visit for those visiting Ubud
One of the most scenic walks to take in Bali. Go in the late afternoon or evening and watch the colours of the sky change. The weather is cooler then too. Highly recommended to visit when in Ubud.
The food here is alright, slightly pricey. It caters to the healthnuts and yogis. The juices and smoothies are good. If you don't know what to pick, go for the Nasi Goreng. It's very flavourful.
Cozy little cafe. Depending on the season, it could get a little too packed sometimes during breakfast. Ask for a table overlooking the garden.

formattedAddress: Grand Hyatt Bali (Kawasan Wisata Nusa Dua BTDC)

tip.text: Dinner with entertainment. The food is top notch. Go for the grilled meats (satay and babi guling are hugely popular). Don't forget to take a picture with the dancers at the end of the show.
Possibly one of the most beautiful restaurants I've seen in Nusa Dua. The architecture is sublime, the food is great and the view is stunning. Great for dinner dates overlooking the Indian Ocean.

location.crossStreet: Kawasan pariwisata Nusa Dua Lot north
formattedAddress: Kawasan Pariwisata Nusa Dua (Kawasan pariwisata Nusa Dua Lot north)

contact.facebookName: Tamarind Kitchen & Lounge at Nusa Dua Beach Hotel & Spa

tip.text: If it's good for the POTUS, it surely is good for me. The grounds are beautiful and so are the rooms (pick the newly renovated ones!). The pools are definitely highlights of the resort.
From the same folks who brought you Bistrot in Seminyak. Love the vintage-y interior and modern interpretation of Balinese food. Try the Nasi Campur! Ayam Kalas was just average (broth was too thin)

formattedAddress: F-8-23A, Pacific Place Commercial Centre (Jalan PJU 1A/4, Ara Damansara)
Pacific Place @ Ara Damansara, Jalan PJU 1A/4A
location.address: Pacific Place @ Ara Damansara, Jalan PJU 1A/4A

tip.text: The pasar malam here doesn't have that many food stalls. You can get tons of fresh fruits and vegetables here though.

This roadside stall serves rather delicious Chinese food. Try the Signature Pork Ribs (RM15) & Sizzling Tofu (RM12). If you're here on a Sunday, do note there is a pasar malam. Be prepared for crowds.
If it's your first time here and you don't know what to order, go for the chicken rice. Tender chicken bathed in light soya. And the dipping sauce is stellar!
Possibly the best curry mee in this neighbourhood. The curry is stellar. Remember to top it off with a serving of roast pork.
The dim sum here is really good, you won't notice that they are halal to begin with. Pork? What pork? Try the salted egg custard bun and the crispy duck chee cheong fun. My must-order each time.
The broth is packed with flavour. By the end of the meal, my bowl was wiped clean. But be warned though, the portion is really small and service is decidedly curt. RM5.50 per bowl.
RM25 for a basic cut. Look for Reuben, he's good. Oh and the show is now known as Wak Doyok Barber Shop.
First time here? Get the Pooh Bear's Favourite. You won't regret it. By far the best waffles you can get in PJ. The honeycomb pieces are everything.
If it's your first time here, order the Siew Yoke Meen and Claypot Loh Shu Fun. This is street food at its best - messy, in your face and oh-so-good! I can't get enough of the sweet garlic sauce!

venue.name: China Town Seng Kee (China Town Seng Kee (唐人街勝記))

tip.text: This hidden bar in the heart of Chinatown checks all the boxes of a perfect evening hangout spot with cocktails so good, you'll be back for more. Order the Assamboi Margarita. It's effin' good! 🙌🏼
If it's your first time here, order the Char Siew & Siew Yuk Wan Tan Mee. You can request for lean meat, if you prefer. This spot is definitely in my Top 5 list for best wan tan mee in PJ.

contact.facebookName: CHAN MENG KEE Restaurant 陳明記燒臘

venue.name: Restoran Chan Meng Kee (陈明记面家)

tip.text: I love the space here. The perfect place to chill out and relax. Grab a spot at the back if you're coming with a group of friends and want a private corner to chat.
Definitely one of the best 'siew yuk' (roast pork) in town. But be mindful that it's rather pricey. RM17 for a strip of roast pork (suitable for a single portion). Two pax with rice = RM38.

venue.name: Wong Mei Kee Restaurant (Wong Mei Kee (王美记) Restaurant)

tip.text: A nice place to spend a quiet romantic evening facing the ocean. I would recommend taking some mosquito repellent as there are plenty here when the sun goes down.

location.crossStreet: at Renaissance Koh Samui Resort & Spa
location.state: จังหวัดสุราษฎร์ธานี
formattedAddress: 208/1 Moo 4 (at Renaissance Koh Samui Resort & Spa)
จังหวัดสุราษฎร์ธานี 84310

tip.text: The food isn't that bad. A bit pricey though but that's what you get eating in this area. I like the Fish & Chips. The Teriyaki Chicken is popular too.
The stir-fried morning glory is delicious. Sadly, the green curry fell short. It was too watered down and not creamy as it should be. It lacked the punch too. Fish cakes were so-so.

venue.name: ระนองโต้รุ่ง2

tip.text: Koh Phaluai is a quiet little island that is perfect for an afternoon siesta. Most tour operators would bring you here after lunch before heading back to Koh Samui.

venue.name: บริษัท สยามรังนกใต้

tip.text: It's my second time here and sad to say, the quality of food has dropped tremendously and prices have increased. I would give this a pass.

venue.name: Mitra Samui Restaurant (มิตรสมุย)

tip.text: Open on Fridays. A must visit for foodies and shopaholics. And I love how huge this Walking Street is. The view in the evenings is especially stunning.
A cozy place to hangout, but there are a lot of mosquitoes buzzing around especially in the evenings.
This was the best Isaan Thai meal I had in Samui. You must try this place if you're in the area. Ask for the popular dishes, delicious all around. Inexpensive too!

location.state: จังหวัดนครศรีธรรมราช
formattedAddress: จังหวัดนครศรีธรรมราช

tip.text: Only on Sunday evenings, starts around 5pm. It's one of the largest walking street night markets, rivaling even the one at Fisherman's Village. The food is yummy. Go where the locals go.

location.state: จังหวัดสุราษฎร์ธานี
formattedAddress: จังหวัดสุราษฎร์ธานี 84310

tip.text: Tip: Order the fresh juices (pick the fruits & the staff will juice them for you) and skip the bottled ones. You can get fresh coconut too. The Samui Egg Benedict is my fave; a must order.

location.crossStreet: at Renaissance Koh Samui Resort & Spa
formattedAddress: 208/1 Moo 4, T. Maret, Laem Nan Beach (at Renaissance Koh Samui Resort & Spa)
location.address: 208/1 Moo 4, T. Maret, Laem Nan Beach

tip.text: If you are a Marriott loyalty member, you get to have two complimentary drinks and also free WIFI access throughout your stay.
Stayed in one of the newly renovated deluxe rooms. It's modern with a hint of Thai influence. The staff is really polite. If you're looking for taxi, my tip is to use the Navigo Samui app. Cheaper.

location.state: จังหวัดสุราษฎร์ธานี
formattedAddress: จังหวัดสุราษฎร์ธานี 84310

venue.name: Renaissance Koh Samui Resort & Spa (โรงแรม เรเนซองส์ เกาะสมุย รีสอร์ทแอนด์สปา)

tip.text: Delicious Thai food but portions are rather small. The Pad Thai is tasty & so is the Belacan Rice. My favourite has to be the Seafood Green Curry! Remember to order dessert (coconut ice cream pulut).

formattedAddress: Ansa Kuala Lumpur (Lot 0.2), Jalan Bukit Bintang
55100 Kuala Lumpur Pusat Bandar, Kuala Lumpur
location.address: Ansa Kuala Lumpur (Lot 0.2), Jalan Bukit Bintang

tip.text: You'll leave feeling happy and healthy too. It's pricey but at least the food tastes good. I ordered the zucchini and pumpkin fritters with smoked salmon and poached egg. Rating: 4/5
You must order the roast chicken with roast pork. Tip: If you like, you can request for your roast pork to be lean and mean.
Hainanese chicken chop is alright. Ask for the sauce to be served separately, otherwise you'll get soggy fries.
Subpar Japanese food. I have tasted better elsewhere at the same price point. Pavilion has more options to choose from. Which makes me wonder why it's usually packed. Oh ya, tourists.
The banana leaf rice is mediocre at best. RM7.50 per set. I still prefer the one from Nirvana's or Devi's. Chicken Varuval is passable but at RM8 per plate, it's a bit too hard to swallow. Gulp.
This is by far my favourite Japanese restaurant this side of town. It specialises solely in tendon and tempura. Service is excellent. Plus, the Japanese chefs are really friendly and boisterous.

formattedAddress: Evolve Concept Mall (Lot EV-G-09 & EV-G-09-AF1), Jalan PJU1A/4
location.address: Evolve Concept Mall (Lot EV-G-09 & EV-G-09-AF1), Jalan PJU1A/4

venue.name: Shitamachi Tendon Akimitsu (下町天丼 秋光)

tip.text: The Bibimbap is tasty but avoid the Seafood Kimchi Fried Rice. It's bland. You can refill your sides of kimchi, cucumber and anchovies.
Quiet spot to chill and escape for a bit. The views are nice here.
The exterior of the building is bright red and you can't miss it. Perfect for some shots for Instagram. The museum gift shop has some interesting items on sale. Worth a visit.
The egg tarts are superb! You MUST try them. I would skip the coconut tarts though. The taste is a bit off. :/

venue.name: Tong Heng Confectionery 東興餅家

tip.text: Order the Mango Shaved Ice. Refreshing especially on a hot, muggy day.

venue.name: Mei Heong Yuen Dessert 味香园

tip.text: It's always packed here. Lots of things to see, eat and buy. Try everything if you must. I visited on the week prior to Chinese New Year and I have to say the mood is delightfully festive.

location.crossStreet: Pagoda St / Mosque St / Temple St
formattedAddress: Chinatown (Pagoda St / Mosque St / Temple St)

tip.text: The Bak Kut Teh here is pepper-based rather than a herb-based broth. Order a set of pork ribs and share. The soup is refillable. Don't forget a side of salted vege and boiled peanuts.

venue.name: Song Fa Bak Kut Teh 松發肉骨茶

tip.text: The private museum tour experience with our host, Alvin is amazing. This is a must visit when you're in Singapore. Learned a lot about the Peranakan culture. No wonder this place comes highly rated.
Nice spot to capture some cool photos. I like the lightness and airiness of the space.
Don't forget to visit here too after exploring Singapore Art Museum. It's just a short distance away.
Cool looking building. They hold concerts and plays here.
Explore your artsy fartsy side.
The hype is mildly justified. Lines get long during peak hours (12pm and 6pm). If possible, come during tea time (3-4pm).

formattedAddress: Stall 10, Maxwell Food Centre (1 Kadayanallur St.)

venue.name: Tian Tian Hainanese Chicken Rice 天天海南鸡饭

tip.text: Lines could be long. Be prepared. Order one of each and try the different variants. The plain one ($0.60/pc) is my fave.
Tourist trap! You can get better food at more affordable prices elsewhere. Avoid, if you can.
The buffet spread is extensive. Love the variety being offered.
The hotel might be dated but the service is as exceptional as ever. You can take home the bear and the rubber duckie in your room. Teehee...
Really tasty and affordable Korean food. Price ranges from RM8-RM15. Try the Bibimbap. It's my favourite. You can always request for more anchovies or kimchi if you want. The boss is really friendly.

formattedAddress: Tuck Shop Food Court, Bangsar Shopping Centre (285, Jalan Maarof, Bukit Bandaraya)
location.address: Tuck Shop Food Court, Bangsar Shopping Centre

tip.text: The bursting meat balls are the best. Try it once and you'll keep going back!

venue.name: Go Noodle House 有间面馆

tip.text: The ramen is always delicious. You can't go wrong with any one of the ramen options from the menu. Tip: If you're there on a weekday, the ramen lunch sets are value for money.

location.address: Lot G110 Ground Floor, Bangsar Shopping Centre
formattedAddress: Lot G110 Ground Floor, Bangsar Shopping Centre

tip.text: Respectable Pan Mee. I like how it tastes but the yolk is not runny enough. I'd give it a 6 out of 10.
Love the Hainanese Chicken Rice here. Opt for the Roast Chicken. The skin is papery thin and crispy. The meat is succulent. The Steamed Chicken is nice too. In the end, it's up to your preference.
The molten egg yolk croissant comes out from the oven at 11:30am and 3:30pm daily. Service is curt. I have met friendlier Filipinos. :\ More of a grab-and-go kind of place.
The weekday tea time specials (3pm - 6pm) are value for money. Prices range from RM4 to RM6 only. Add on chicken karaage and refillable green tea for RM4.
Love the Roast Pork and Barbecued Pork (Char Siew, Siew Yuk) here. One of the best in my opinion. It's Cantonese style. Request for lean meat if you don't like your pork to be too fatty.
It's all about the delicious and artery-choking Mee Pok (noodles with minced pork and crispy pork lard). Yummy! The place is rather cramped esp during weekends. Hainanese Tea is a must!
Nasi Lemak Ayam Kunyit was just okay. It's like your regular Nasi Lemak. Nothing much to shout about.
The 'Chu Char' or 'Tai Chow' in the evening is delicious and value-for-money. Try the Dry Butter Chicken and Signature Claypot Taufu. The wait could be long, so be patient.

location.address: No. 54, Jalan PJU 1/45, Aman Suria Damansara
formattedAddress: No. 54, Jalan PJU 1/45, Aman Suria Damansara

venue.name: 好月楼海鲜餐馆 Hao Yue Lou Seafood Restaurant

tip.text: Order the Chicken Noodle Soup (a.k.a. Koay Teow Th'ng or Hor Fun). Generous portion and ingredients. You'll get the signature steamed chicken, pork slice and fish balls. The chicken rice is great too!

venue.name: Restoran Prosperity Bowl 公雞碗菜園雞

tip.text: Pizzas by the slice or by the pie. If you're a small eater, one slice is enough. Try the frozen custard next door. Rather yummy. You can always asks for a sample first.
They make your ice cream when you order on the super cold steel pan. Love how creamy it is. Not that sweet too, which is good. It's a franchise from Bangkok's Central World Mall. RM15 per cup.
Don't order the Signature Coconut Shake. Instead of keeping it simple, they added to much nonsense in it like jelly, etc. making it cloyingly sweet. Will I return? Hmm... Probably not.

formattedAddress: G-B.02 BU11. Oasis business centre (Persiaran Tropicana)

tip.text: Food is on the expensive side. Delicious though. It's always crowded especially on the weekends (after 7pm). Order the Signature Tofu and Salted Egg Mantis Prawns.

formattedAddress: H-18-G, Jalan PJU 1/45, Aman Suria Damansara (Jalan PJU 1/45)
location.address: H-18-G, Jalan PJU 1/45, Aman Suria Damansara

tip.text: Cheap and good! Authentic Hainanese cuisine which is a rare find. Try the Braised Potato with Pork and Signature Chai Poh Egg. Would definitely come back for more visits.
You MUST try the kaya! It's only RM4.80.
It's on the pricey side but delicious nevertheless. Ask the waiter to recommend you some signature dishes like the otak-otak and stir fry fern leaf with tuna.
Perfect spot for breakfast. Must order: Ipoh Hor Fun (add the meatballs) and the Toast Bread with Butter and Kaya (Roti Kahwin). Don't forget to also order a tall glass of White Coffee to go with it.

venue.name: Restoran Ipoh Chang Jiang White Coffee 怡保长江白咖啡馆

tip.text: The lunch sets are value-for-money (each at RM19.90++). I tried the Green Curry and it's really rich and flavourful. Comparable to some of the best I've had. Would definitely recommend this spot.
Value for money rice set dishes. Try the Dry Butter Mantis Prawn or the Marmite Pork Ribs. The Salted Egg Fried Rice is their "chiu pai" a.k.a. house specialty.

formattedAddress: 86-1 Block G, Jln PJU 1/3B (Sunwaymas Commercial Centre)

tip.text: The Wan Tan Mee with Char Siew is good. I also like the herbal duck leg noodles. This is the offshoot from the main Pun Chun Restaurant in Bidor. Ample free parking space here which is a plus.

formattedAddress: H-G-21, Block H, Jalan PJU 1A/3, Taipan 2 Damansara, Ara Damansara, (Ara Damansara)
location.address: H-G-21, Block H, Jalan PJU 1A/3, Taipan 2 Damansara, Ara Damansara,

venue.name: Pun Chun Noodle House 品珍面之家

tip.text: Love the view of Putrajaya from here. You can learn Stand-Up Yoga here. And they even have Stand-Up Paddleboard classes too.
Service is good and prompt. Dining area could be a bit cramped. The WiFi is a bit wonky. Food is great.
The cooking classes here are awesome. Went to one taught by Chef Qistina and had tons of fun. The food is so good!
There are 2 things you have to order whenever you're here: the Char Siew Pau (steamed pork buns) and Loh Mai Kai (glutinous pork rice). I rest my case.

venue.name: Restoran Key Hiong (Dim Sum) (奇香饱饺点心)

tip.text: Cozy spot for a cuppa latte and some light snacks. It's the perfect escape from the busy Changkat Bukit Bintang nearby.
You have to pay a surcharge if you dine inside the air-conditioned restaurant. Sitting al fresco is better anyway. 😁
A bit of a letdown. Ordered the Lemon Pie and Nyonya Delight. Flavour of the softserve was meh. You can choose between Pink Peppercorn or Seasonal; which was Black Sesame. Will I return? Nope.
What differentiates each of the ice cream on the menu is the toppings. And nothing much. Bordering on an overpriced disaster. The only consolation is the Instagram-worthy interior. The end.
It's expensive (hey, you're in Bangsar) but delicious nevertheless. Marmite chicken = yum. Take a seat outside and people watch. You'll see your fair share of Datuks, Datins, Expats, Rich Folks, etc.

formattedAddress: 59100 Kuala Lumpur, Federal Territory of Kuala Lum

tip.text: You braved through city traffic for only one reason: the beef ball noodles. In terms of taste, it's not that different from the branch at Lot 10 Hutong food court. Still just as good.

formattedAddress: 3, Jln. Tun Tan Siew Sin (off Jln. Silang)

venue.name: Restoran Soong Kee Beef Ball Noodle (颂记牛肉丸粉)

tip.text: From the same people who brought you KEDAI next door. Affordable and cheap food. Try the Chai Latte and get a pasta to go with it.
Need some custom wood furniture? This is the place to be. The owners and workers are really friendly. Support your local makers and get something specially made for your home or workspace.
Order anything with Bursting Meatballs in it. Trust me. You'll love them. The Superior Soup is my pick. The Spicy one is just so-so.

formattedAddress: 61-P1, Block D, The School, Jaya One
location.address: 61-P1, Block D, The School, Jaya One

contact.facebookName: 有間麵館 GO Noodle House

venue.name: Go Noodle House 有間麵館

tip.text: Order the Roast Duck and Siew Yuk (Roast Pork) combo. It's open from Mon to Sat. The Roast Duck sells out fast. You can request for extra lean meat for your Siew Yuk if you want.
I really like the Thai food here. Inexpensive and delicious. The Mango Salad and Crispy Squid are my faves.

formattedAddress: L 27 Block L, Taipan Damansara 2 (Jalan PJU1a/1 Ara Damansara)

tip.text: Came here for breakfast on a Saturday. Service was slow as they were understaffed. Really pricey. It wouldn't warrant a repeat visit.

formattedAddress: Verve Shops, Jalan Kiara 5 (G-5, Ground Floor)

tip.text: You can make your own breakfast set here (5 choices, RM15.90). Not too bad but would it warrant a second visit? I'm not quite sure. It didn't leave much of an impression.
Food is tasty. And service is friendly and prompt. But it's a bit on the pricey side. Two dishes (Sesame Chicken and Kailan; requested for small portions) for two persons amounted to RM30++. Gulp.

venue.name: Restoran Makanan Laut Wang Chiew 黄记
